              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Taking an Apprentice</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2349"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2349"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=6065">Paul "Dark Raptor" McKelvey</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 6065 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">A How too on getting new players in the game.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">How to: Find and Train new players<br>
<br>
One of the skills that we all need to start practicing in mass. While it may be true that new players come to the game on there own, it benefits us all to take on an apprentice so to speak. In order to successfully do this there are a few simple steps to take. I hope to cover these main points in this article and hopefully we can grab some more players.<br>
<br>
1.	Rescuing a new player from another game<br>
<br>
While I know a lot of SWCCG players play other games there are some CCG players who still play only one game. The first step to finding new players is to play the game at your local card shop to show people the game and that it even exists. Play it right next to other games. The worst thing to see in my opinion is a magic or pokemon player saying something like I want to play that game but I don&amp;#8217;t know how or its too hard. This is where you have to take the initiative. Be cool about it. Play a game of magic or two or even&amp;#8230;Pokemon then say to the person something like this game is cool but its no star wars. Show them your decks and explain to them the basics of the game like how you win and what the object is. You might even want to play a game with your friend and have them watch. Make sure you DO NOT play a game that will be boring such as Jedi training or Manip. These will be quick deterrents to your young apprentice unless they showed an interest in that aspect of the game. If they show an interest in the game offer to show them how to play and get a few games going and let them win even. It will boost their confidence in the game and instill in them the drive to win.<br>
<br>
2.	Teaching your new player the game<br>
<br>
Once you have the new player interested, play them but dont over play them. You don t want to play the game all the time and over do it. When you go to teach or play the new player don t use any thing you would consider tech. You want to keep the game as simple as possible to keep the new player interested. Make the games fun filled with lots of battles. You might even want to make special decks with the sole purpose of battling with few interrupts and lots of characters, mostly mains. When a player sees a main they think of the movies and the powerful characters, not storm troopers and ywings. Youll want to teach battling the most and cover other aspects later on. Slowly as the player evolves youll want to add more interrupts and tech cards to teach the player the higher complexities of the game.<br>
<br>
3.	Decks for your new player<br>
<br>
This is maybe one of the funniest things about teaching a new player. You have to stretch your skills and your commons to build two new decks for your newbie. Sure they may be scrub decks but weve all been there. This will not only give your apprentice a huge head start on the game but something to work towards and even more incentive to be in the game. Youd be amazed how quickly someone just entering the game will trade away a different card game for star wars. And of course you can help as much as you can by bumping down all your lose rares in other words the rares you left on the table after the tourney. After a few weeks with these decks the new player will be ready for a tourney.<br>
<br>
4.	Training for the advanced newbie aka the first tourney<br>
<br>
This is where it starts to get hard. Your apprentice is no longer the newbie he once was and is ready for a tourney. This is also where you have to be your most cautious in keeping the new player interested. You dont want your apprentice to be beat on&amp;#8230; to bad and you mostly want them to have fun, this is where they hang in the balance and can either keep up the game or drop to the pokemon side of the force. You yourself have to also be very careful when playing your apprentice. Keep in mind that you can win, but don t wins. See where you could have and take advantage of it but keep the player interested. If you beat down the apprentice too hard, they will fell that they are to poor to go to the tourney. Here are a few simple things to help your apprentice before the tourney. <br>
<br>
The companion. Be a friend. If your teaching this person how to play, odds are that if they stick with the game youll be going to tourney together and will become friends anyway.<br>
<br>
The Decks. If you have extra decks let them borrow one of yours. It gives them more of a fighting chance and a chance for you to find out how one of your other decks works.<br>
<br>
<br>
The Stick. The stick is basically that. You place a stick next to you and your apprentice during the game and watch them while they play. When they do something wrong or forget to force drain, give them a little tap with the stick. <br>
<br>
The stick may be a little extreme but it works trust me. After the tourney you have to tell youre apprentice no matter how bad he did that he did a good job and tell the story of how bad you did your first time. <br>
<br>
If you do all that is in this article and then some more that youll have to learn from experience youll be able to bring new players into the game in a matter of weeks. If you want results look at Kyle Ishimaru, Brandon Bale, and a few other floating around that I taught. If you want more info D-mail me. Adding players to the game makes us all better players as well as making us all have more fun. <br>
 </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2349"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2349"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=2349" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
